[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] In mathematics, **Church encoding** is a way of representing various types of data in the lambda calculus.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] In the untyped lambda calculus the only primitive data type are functions, represented by lambda abstraction terms.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Types that are usually considered primitive in other notations (such as integers, Booleans, pairs, lists, and tagged unions) are not natively present.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Hence the need arises to have ways to represent the data of these varying types by lambda terms, that is, by functions that are taking functions as their arguments and are returning functions as their results.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] The **Church numerals** are a representation of the natural numbers using lambda notation.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] The method is named for Alonzo Church, who first encoded data in the lambda calculus this way.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] It can also be extended to represent other data types in the similar spirit.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] This article makes occasional use of the alternative syntax for lambda abstraction terms, where λ*x*.λ*y*.λ*z*.*N* is abbreviated as λ*xyz*.*N*, as well as the two standard combinators, $I\equiv \lambda x.x$ and $K\equiv \lambda xy.x$ , as needed.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Church pairs are the Church encoding of the pair (two-tuple) type.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] To have two things is to be able to supply them to any observer expecting of two things.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] The pair is thus represented as a function that takes a function argument.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] The pair itself does not decide what to do with the elements of the tuple.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] When given its argument it will apply the argument to the two components of the pair.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Boolean logic embodies a *choice* between *two* alternatives.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] These definitions allow predicates (i.e. functions returning logical values) to directly act as *if-test* clauses, so that *if* operator is just an identity function, and thus can be omitted.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Each logical value already acts as an *if*, performing a choice between its two arguments.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] A Boolean value applied to two values returns either the first or the second value.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] returns *then-clause* if *test-clause* is *true*, and *else-clause* if *test-clause* is *false*.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Because logical values like *true* and *false* choose their first or second argument, they can be combined to provide logical operators.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Several implementations are usually possible, whether by directly manipulating parameters or by reducing to the more basic logical values.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Church numerals are the representations of natural numbers under Church encoding.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] The higher-order function that represents natural number *n* is a function that maps any function f to its *n*-fold composition.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Church encoding is thus a *unary* encoding of natural numbers, corresponding to simple counting.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Each Church numeral achieves this by construction.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] All Church numerals are functions that take two parameters.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] applying the function three times in a row, etc.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] The Church numeral **3** is a chain of three applications of any given function in sequence, starting from some value.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] The supplied function is first applied to a supplied argument and then successively to its own result.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] The end result is not the number 3 (unless the supplied parameter happens to be 0 and the function is a successor function).
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] The function itself, and not its end result, is the Church numeral **3**.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] The Church numeral **3** means simply to do something three times.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] It is an ostensive demonstration of what is meant by "three times".
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Arithmetic operations on numbers produce numbers as their results.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] In Church encoding, these operations are represented by lambda abstractions which, when applied to Church numerals representing the operands, beta-reduce to the Church numerals representing the results.
