[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Most real-world languages have support for machine-native integers; the *church* and *unchurch* functions convert between nonnegative integers and their corresponding Church numerals.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] The functions are given here in Haskell, where the `\` corresponds to the λ of Lambda calculus.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Implementations in other languages are similar.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] One simple approach for extending Church Numerals to signed numbers is to use a Church pair, containing Church numerals representing a positive and a negative value.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] The integer value is the difference between the two Church numerals.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Negation is performed by swapping the values.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] The integer value is more naturally represented if one of the pair is zero.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] A similar definition is given here for division, except in this definition, one value in each pair must be zero (see *OneZero* above).
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] The *divZ* function allows us to ignore the value that has a zero component.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Rational and computable real numbers may also be encoded in lambda calculus.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Rational numbers may be encoded as a pair of signed numbers.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Computable real numbers may be encoded by a limiting process that guarantees that the difference from the real value differs by a number which may be made as small as we need.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] The references given describe software that could, in theory, be translated into lambda calculus.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Once real numbers are defined, complex numbers are naturally encoded as a pair of real numbers.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] The data types and functions described above demonstrate that any data type or calculation may be encoded in lambda calculus.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] A representation of lists should provide ways to implement these operations.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] The archetypal lambda calculus representation of lists is Church List encoding.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] It represents lists as right folds, as functions to return the results of folding over the list with user-supplied arguments.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] It follows the paradigm of "a thing is the result of its observation".
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] No matter the concrete implementation, folding a given list of values results in the same result.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] This provides an abstract view at what a list is.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Church List encoding is such a mechanism.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] On the other hand, seen more concretely, lists can be represented as a sequence of linked list nodes.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] This is the original Church encoding for lists.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] A list is represented by a binary function, that, when supplied with two arguments, – a "combining function" and a "sentinel value", – will perform the right fold of the encoded list using those two arguments.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] For an empty list the sentinel value is returned as the folding's result.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] The result of folding a non-empty list with *head* h and *tail* t is the result of combining, by the supplied function, of the *head* h with the *result* of folding the tail t with the supplied two arguments.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Thus the combining function's two arguments are, conceptually, the *current element* and the *result* of folding the *rest* of the list.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] For example, a list of three elements x, y and z is represented by a term that when applied to c and n returns c x (c y (c z n)).
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Equivalently, it is an application of the chain of functional compositions ( $\circ$ ) of partial applications, ((c x) $\circ$ (c y) $\circ$ (c z)) n.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] where $\{\ l\ \}=\lambda \,c\,n.fold\ c\ n\ l$ denotes the Church List representation of the list l .
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Since Church encoded list is its own folding function, folding it just means applying that function to the supplied arguments.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] This list representation can be given type in System F.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] The evident correspondence to Church numerals is non-coincidental, as that can be seen as a unary encoding, with natural numbers represented by lists of unit (i.e. non-important) values, e.g. [() () ()], with the list's length serving as the representation of the natural number.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Right folding over such lists uses functions which necessarily ignore the element's value, and is equivalent to the chained functional composition, i.e.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] However this does not give a representation of the empty list, because there is no "null" pointer.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] In a *nil* node *second* is never accessed, provided that **head** and **tail** are only applied to nonempty lists.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Scott encoding for data types follows their surface syntax without regard to recursion in the data type.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Given all the handlers as arguments, the datum representation function will then call the appropriate handler with the corresponding internal data.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Scott encoded values can thus be said to embody the pattern matching case handling for their data type.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Recursive operations on Scott lists typically require explicit use of recursion, e.g. using $\operatorname {Y}$ combinator, or explicit self-application definitions.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] One such example is *fold*, unlike the no-op that it is under Church encoding.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] But *tail* is immediately available, so its definition is much simpler here, in comparison.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Scott encoding can be seen as using the idea of continuations, which can lead to simpler code.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] In this approach, we use the fact that lists can be observed using pattern matching expression.
