[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] More generally, an algebraic data type with m alternatives becomes a function with m parameters.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] When the i th constructor has $n_{i}$ arguments, the corresponding parameter of the encoding takes $n_{i}$ arguments as well.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Scott encoding can be done in untyped lambda calculus, whereas its use with types requires a type system with recursion and type polymorphism.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] A list that can be used to compute arbitrary types would have a type that quantifies over `C`.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] A list generic in `E` would also take `E` as the type argument.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] A straightforward implementation of Church encoding slows some access operations from $O(1)$ to $O(n)$ , where n is the size of the data structure, making Church encoding impractical.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Research has shown that this can be addressed by targeted optimizations, but most functional programming languages instead expand their intermediate representations to contain algebraic data types.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Nonetheless Church encoding is often used in theoretical arguments, as it is a natural representation for partial evaluation and theorem proving.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Operations can be typed using higher-ranked types, and primitive recursion is easily accessible.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] The assumption that functions are the only primitive data types streamlines many proofs.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Church encoding is complete but only representationally.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Additional functions are needed to translate the representation into common data types, for display to people.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] It is not possible in general to decide if two functions are extensionally equal due to the undecidability of equivalence from Church's theorem.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] The translation may apply the function in some way to retrieve the value it represents, or look up its value as a literal lambda term.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] Lambda calculus is usually interpreted as using intensional equality.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/church-encoding] There are potential problems with the interpretation of results because of the difference between the intensional and extensional definition of equality.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Combinatory logic was originally intended as a 'pre-logic' that would clarify the role of quantified variables in logic, essentially by eliminating them.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Another way of eliminating quantified variables is Quine's predicate functor logic.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] While the expressive power of combinatory logic typically exceeds that of first-order logic, the expressive power of predicate functor logic is identical to that of first-order logic (Quine 1960, 1966, 1976).
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] The inventor of combinatory logic, Moses Schönfinkel, published nothing on combinatory logic after his original 1924 paper.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Haskell Curry rediscovered the combinators while working as an instructor at Princeton University in late 1927.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] In the late 1930s, Alonzo Church and his students at Princeton invented a rival formalism for functional abstraction, the lambda calculus, which proved more popular than combinatory logic.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] The upshot of these historical contingencies was that until theoretical computer science began taking an interest in combinatory logic in the 1960s and 1970s, nearly all work on the subject was by Haskell Curry and his students, or by Robert Feys in Belgium.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Curry and Feys (1958), and Curry *et al.* (1972) survey the early history of combinatory logic.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] For a more modern treatment of combinatory logic and the lambda calculus together, see the book by Barendregt, which reviews the models Dana Scott devised for combinatory logic in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] In computer science, combinatory logic is used as a simplified model of computation, used in computability theory and proof theory.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Despite its simplicity, combinatory logic captures many essential features of computation.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Combinatory logic can be viewed as a variant of the lambda calculus, in which lambda expressions (representing functional abstraction) are replaced by a limited set of *combinators*, primitive functions without free variables.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] It is easy to transform lambda expressions into combinator expressions, and combinator reduction is much simpler than lambda reduction.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Hence combinatory logic has been used to model some non-strict functional programming languages and hardware.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] The purest form of this view is the programming language Unlambda, whose sole primitives are the S and K combinators augmented with character input/output.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Although not a practical programming language, Unlambda is of some theoretical interest.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Combinatory logic can be given a variety of interpretations.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Many early papers by Curry showed how to translate axiom sets for conventional logic into combinatory logic equations.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Dana Scott in the 1960s and 1970s showed how to marry model theory and combinatory logic.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] where v is a variable name drawn from a predefined infinite set of variable names, and $E_{1}$ and $E_{2}$ are lambda-terms.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Terms of the form $\lambda v.E_{1}$ are called *abstractions*.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] The variable v is called the formal parameter of the abstraction, and $E_{1}$ is the *body* of the abstraction.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] The term $\lambda v.E_{1}$ represents the function which, applied to an argument, binds the formal parameter v to the argument and then computes the resulting value of $E_{1}$ — that is, it returns $E_{1}$ , with every occurrence of v replaced by the argument.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Terms of the form $E_{1}E_{2}$ are called *applications*.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Applications model function invocation or execution: the function represented by $E_{1}$ is to be invoked, with $E_{2}$ as its argument, and the result is computed.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] If $E_{1}$ (sometimes called the *applicand*) is an abstraction, the term may be *reduced*: $E_{2}$ , the argument, may be substituted into the body of $E_{1}$ in place of the formal parameter of $E_{1}$ , and the result is a new lambda term which is *equivalent* to the old one.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] If a lambda term contains no subterms of the form $((\lambda v.E_{1})E_{2})$ then it cannot be reduced, and is said to be in normal form.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] The expression $E[v:=a]$ represents the result of taking the term E and replacing all free occurrences of v in it with a .
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] By convention, we take $(abc)$ as shorthand for $((ab)c)$ (i.e., application is left associative).
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] The motivation for this definition of reduction is that it captures the essential behavior of all mathematical functions.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] For example, consider the function that computes the square of a number.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] (Using " * " to indicate multiplication.) x here is the formal parameter of the function.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] To evaluate the resulting expression $3*3$ , we would have to resort to our knowledge of multiplication and the number 3.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Since any computation is simply a composition of the evaluation of suitable functions on suitable primitive arguments, this simple substitution principle suffices to capture the essential mechanism of computation.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Moreover, in lambda calculus, notions such as '3' and ' * ' can be represented without any need for externally defined primitive operators or constants.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] It is possible to identify terms in lambda calculus, which, when suitably interpreted, behave like the number 3 and like the multiplication operator, q.v.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Lambda calculus is known to be computationally equivalent in power to many other plausible models for computation (including Turing machines); that is, any calculation that can be accomplished in any of these other models can be expressed in lambda calculus, and vice versa.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] According to the Church–Turing thesis, both models can express any possible computation.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] It is perhaps surprising that lambda-calculus can represent any conceivable computation using only the simple notions of function abstraction and application based on simple textual substitution of terms for variables.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] But even more remarkable is that abstraction is not even required.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] *Combinatory logic* is a model of computation equivalent to lambda calculus, but without abstraction.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] The advantage of this is that evaluating expressions in lambda calculus is quite complicated because the semantics of substitution must be specified with great care to avoid variable capture problems.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] In contrast, evaluating expressions in combinatory logic is much simpler, because there is no notion of substitution.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Since abstraction is the only way to manufacture functions in the lambda calculus, something must replace it in the combinatory calculus.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Instead of abstraction, combinatory calculus provides a limited set of primitive functions out of which other functions may be built.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] The primitive functions are *combinators*, or functions that, when seen as lambda terms, contain no free variables.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] This is the same general convention (left-associativity) as for multiple application in lambda calculus.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] where E is a term mentioning only variables from the set $\{x_{1}\dots x_{n}\}$ .
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] It is in this way that primitive combinators behave as functions.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] S applies x to y after first substituting z into each of them.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Or put another way, x is applied to y inside the environment z .
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Note that although $((S\,K\,K)\,x)=(Ix)$ for any x , $(S\,K\,K)$ itself is not equal to I .
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] We say the terms are extensionally equal.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Extensional equality captures the mathematical notion of the equality of functions: that two functions are considered *equal* if they always produce the same results for the same arguments.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] In contrast, the terms themselves, together with the reduction of primitive combinators, capture the notion of *intensional equality* of functions: that two functions are considered *equal* only if they have identical implementations up to the expansion of primitive combinators.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] There are many ways to implement an identity function; $(S\,K\,K)$ and I are among these ways. $(S\,K\,S)$ is yet another.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] We will use the word *equivalent* to mean extensional equality.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] A more interesting combinator is the fixed point combinator or Y combinator, which can be used to implement recursion.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Note that *T*[ ] as given is not a well-typed mathematical function, but rather a term rewriter: Although it eventually yields a combinator, the transformation may generate intermediary expressions that are neither lambda terms nor combinators, via rule (5).
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] This process is also known as *abstraction elimination*.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] This definition is exhaustive: any lambda expression will be subject to exactly one of these rules (see Summary of lambda calculus above).
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] It is related to the process of *bracket abstraction*, which takes an expression *E* built from variables and application and produces a combinator expression [x]E in which the variable x is not free, such that [*x*]*E x* = *E* holds.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Bracket abstraction induces a translation from lambda terms to combinator expressions, by interpreting lambda-abstractions using the bracket abstraction algorithm.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] In general, the *T*[ ] construction may expand a lambda term of length *n* to a combinatorial term of length Θ(*n*3).
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] The *T*[ ] transformation is motivated by a desire to eliminate abstraction.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Two special cases, rules 3 and 4, are trivial: *λx*.*x* is clearly equivalent to **I**, and *λx*.*E* is clearly equivalent to (**K** *T*[*E*]) if *x* does not appear free in *E*.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] The first two rules are also simple: Variables convert to themselves, and applications, which are allowed in combinatory terms, are converted to combinators simply by converting the applicand and the argument to combinators.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] It is rules 5 and 6 that are of interest.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Rule 5 simply says that to convert a complex abstraction to a combinator, we must first convert its body to a combinator, and then eliminate the abstraction.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Rule 6 actually eliminates the abstraction.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] *E*1 and *E*2 each contain strictly fewer applications than (*E*1 *E*2), so the recursion must terminate in a lambda term with no applications at all—either a variable, or a term of the form *λx*.*E*.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] With the η-reduction rule, *λf*.*λx*.(*f* *x*) is transformed into **I**.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] There are one-point bases from which every combinator can be composed extensionally equal to *any* lambda term.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Since {**K**, **S**} is a basis, it follows that {**X**} is a basis too.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] The Iota programming language uses **X** as its sole combinator.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] In fact, there exist infinitely many such bases.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] These combinators are extremely useful when translating predicate logic or lambda calculus into combinator expressions.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] They were also used by Curry, and much later by David Turner, whose name has been associated with their computational use.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] The motivation here is that **B** and **C** are limited versions of **S**.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Whereas **S** takes a value and substitutes it into both the applicand and its argument before performing the application, **C** performs the substitution only in the applicand, and **B** only in the argument.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] The modern names for the combinators come from Haskell Curry's doctoral thesis of 1930 (see B, C, K, W System).
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] The reduction in combinator size that results from the new transformation rules can also be achieved without introducing **B** and **C**, as demonstrated in Section 3.2 of Tromp (2008).
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] A distinction must be made between the **CL**K as described in this article and the **CL**I calculus.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] The distinction corresponds to that between the λK and the λI calculus.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] As a consequence, combinator **K** is not present in the λI calculus nor in the **CL**I calculus.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] The constants of **CL**I are: **I**, **B**, **C** and **S**, which form a basis from which all **CL**I terms can be composed (modulo equality).
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Every λI term can be converted into an extensionally equal **CL**I combinator according to rules similar to those presented above for the conversion of λK terms into **CL**K combinators.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Note, however, that this transformation is not the inverse transformation of any of the versions of *T*[ ] that we have seen.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] A normal form is any combinatory term in which the primitive combinators that occur, if any, are not applied to enough arguments to be simplified.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] It is undecidable whether a general combinatory term has a normal form; whether two combinatory terms are equivalent, etc.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] This can be shown in a similar way as for the corresponding problems for lambda terms.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] The undecidable problems above (equivalence, existence of normal form, etc.) take as input syntactic representations of terms under a suitable encoding (e.g., Church encoding).
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] One may also consider a toy trivial computation model where we "compute" properties of terms by means of combinators applied directly to the terms themselves as arguments, rather than to their syntactic representations.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] A predicate **N** is *nontrivial* if there are two arguments *A* and *B* such that **N** *A* = **T** and **N** *B* = **F**.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] A combinator **N** is *complete* if **N***M* has a normal form for every argument *M*.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] An analogue of Rice's theorem for this toy model then says that every complete predicate is trivial.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] The proof of this theorem is rather simple.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Suppose there is a complete non trivial predicate, say **N**.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Hence (**N** ABSURDUM) is neither **T** nor **F**, which contradicts the presupposition that **N** would be a complete non trivial predicate.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] From this undefinability theorem it immediately follows that there is no complete predicate that can discriminate between terms that have a normal form and terms that do not have a normal form.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] If EQUAL would exist, then for all *A*, *λx.*(EQUAL *x A*) would have to be a complete non trivial predicate.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] This shows that definability by predicates is a not a reasonable model of decidability.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] David Turner used his combinators to implement the SASL programming language.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Iverson used primitives based on Curry's combinators in his J programming language, a successor to APL.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] This enabled what Iverson called tacit programming, that is, programming in functional expressions containing no variables, along with powerful tools for working with such programs.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] It turns out that tacit programming is possible in any APL-like language with user-defined operators.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] The Curry–Howard isomorphism implies a connection between logic and programming: every proof of a theorem of intuitionistic logic corresponds to a reduction of a typed lambda term, and conversely.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Moreover, theorems can be identified with function type signatures.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Specifically, a typed combinatory logic corresponds to a Hilbert system in proof theory.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] The calculus consisting of **AK**, **AS**, and **MP** is complete for the implicational fragment of the intuitionistic logic, which can be seen as follows.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Consider the set *W* of all deductively closed sets of formulas, ordered by inclusion.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] This definition obeys the conditions on satisfaction of →: on one hand, if $X\Vdash A\to B$ , and $Y\in W$ is such that $Y\supseteq X$ and $Y\Vdash A$ , then $Y\Vdash B$ by modus ponens.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] On the other hand, if $X\not \Vdash A\to B$ , then $X,A\not \vdash B$ by the deduction theorem, thus the deductive closure of $X\cup \{A\}$ is an element $Y\in W$ such that $Y\supseteq X$ , $Y\Vdash A$ , and $Y\not \Vdash B$ .
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Let *A* be any formula which is not provable in the calculus.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/combinatory-logic] Then *A* does not belong to the deductive closure *X* of the empty set, thus $X\not \Vdash A$ , and *A* is not intuitionistically valid.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] In abstract rewriting, an object is in **normal form** if it cannot be rewritten any further, i.e. it is irreducible.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] Depending on the rewriting system, an object may rewrite to several normal forms or none at all.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] Many properties of rewriting systems relate to normal forms.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] Stated formally, if (*A*,→) is an abstract rewriting system, *x*∈*A* is in **normal form** if no *y*∈*A* exists such that *x*→*y*, i.e.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] An object *a* is **weakly normalizing** if there exists at least one particular sequence of rewrites starting from *a* that eventually yields a normal form.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] A rewriting system has the **weak normalization property** or is *(weakly) normalizing* (WN) if every object is weakly normalizing.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] An object *a* is **strongly normalizing** if every sequence of rewrites starting from *a* eventually terminates with a normal form.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] A rewriting system is *strongly normalizing*, *terminating*, *noetherian*, or has the **(strong) normalization property** (SN), if each of its objects is strongly normalizing.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] A rewriting system has the *normal form property* (NF) if for all objects *a* and normal forms *b*, *b* can be reached from *a* by a series of rewrites and inverse rewrites only if *a* reduces to *b*.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] A rewriting system has the *unique normal form property* (UN) if for all normal forms *a*, *b* ∈ *S*, *a* can be reached from *b* by a series of rewrites and inverse rewrites only if *a* is equal to *b*.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] A rewriting system has the *unique normal form property with respect to reduction* (UN→) if for every term reducing to normal forms *a* and *b*, *a* is equal to *b*.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] This section presents some well known results.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] Confluence (abbreviated CR) implies NF implies UN implies UN→.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] Hence CR, NF, UN, and UN→ coincide if WN holds.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] One example is that simplifying arithmetic expressions produces a number - in arithmetic, all numbers are normal forms.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] Examples of non-normalizing systems (not weakly or strongly) include counting to infinity (1 ⇒ 2 ⇒ 3 ⇒ ...) and loops such as the transformation function of the Collatz conjecture (1 ⇒ 2 ⇒ 4 ⇒ 1 ⇒ ..., it is an open problem if there are any other loops of the Collatz transformation).
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] Another example is the single-rule system { *r*(*x*,*y*) → *r*(*y*,*x*) }, which has no normalizing properties since from any term, e.g.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] *r*(4,2) a single rewrite sequence starts, viz.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] This leads to the idea of rewriting "modulo commutativity" where a term is in normal form if no rules but commutativity apply.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] The system {*b* → *a*, *b* → *c*, *c* → *b*, *c* → *d*} (pictured) is an example of a weakly normalizing but not strongly normalizing system.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] *a* and *d* are normal forms, and *b* and *c* can be reduced to *a* or *d*, but the infinite reduction *b* → *c* → *b* → *c* → ... means that neither *b* nor *c* is strongly normalizing.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] The pure untyped lambda calculus does not satisfy the strong normalization property, and not even the weak normalization property.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] Consider the term $\lambda x.xxx$ (application is left associative).
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] Therefore, the term $(\lambda x.xxx)(\lambda x.xxx)$ is not strongly normalizing.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] And this is the only reduction sequence, hence it is not weakly normalizing either.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] Various systems of typed lambda calculus including the simply typed lambda calculus, Jean-Yves Girard's System F, and Thierry Coquand's calculus of constructions are strongly normalizing.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] A lambda calculus system with the normalization property can be viewed as a programming language with the property that every program terminates.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] Although this is a very useful property, it has a drawback: a programming language with the normalization property cannot be Turing complete, otherwise one could solve the halting problem by seeing if the program type checks.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] This means that there are computable functions that cannot be defined in the simply typed lambda calculus, and similarly for the calculus of constructions and System F.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/normalization-property-abstract-rewriting] A typical example is that of a self-interpreter in a total programming language.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] The **simply typed lambda calculus** (⁠ $\lambda ^{\to }$ ⁠), a form of type theory, is a typed interpretation of the lambda calculus with only one type constructor (⁠ $\to$ ⁠) that builds function types.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] It is the canonical and simplest example of a typed lambda calculus.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] The simply typed lambda calculus was originally introduced by Alonzo Church in 1940 as an attempt to avoid paradoxical use of the untyped lambda calculus.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] The term *simple type* is also used to refer to extensions of the simply typed lambda calculus with constructs such as products, coproducts or natural numbers (System T) or even full recursion (like PCF).
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] In contrast, systems that introduce polymorphic types (like System F) or dependent types (like the Logical Framework) are not considered *simply typed*.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] The simple types, except for full recursion, are still considered *simple* because the Church encodings of such structures can be done using only $\to$ and suitable type variables, while polymorphism and dependency cannot.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] This finite set of rules included rule V *modus ponens* as well as IV and VI for substitution and generalization respectively.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] Rules I to III are known as alpha, beta, and eta conversion in the lambda calculus.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] Church sought to use English only as a syntax language (that is, a metamathematical language) for describing symbolic expressions with no interpretations.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] In 1940 Church settled on a subscript notation for denoting the type in a symbolic expression.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] In his presentation, Church used only two base types: o for "the type of propositions" and $\iota$ for "the type of individuals".
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] The type o has no term constants, whereas $\iota$ has one term constant.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] Frequently the calculus with only one base type, usually ⁠ o ⁠, is considered.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] The Greek letter subscripts ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠, ⁠ $\beta$ ⁠, etc. denote type variables; the parenthesized subscripted $(\alpha \beta )$ denotes the function type ⁠ $\beta \to \alpha$ ⁠.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] Church 1940 p.58 used 'arrow or ⁠ $\to$ ⁠' to denote *stands for*, or *is an abbreviation for*.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] By the 1970s stand-alone arrow notation was in use; for example in this article non-subscripted symbols $\sigma$ and $\tau$ can range over types.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] The infinite number of axioms were then seen to be a consequence of applying rules I to VI to the types (see Peano axioms).
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] Informally, the *function type* $\sigma \to \tau$ refers to the type of functions that, given an input of type ⁠ $\sigma$ ⁠, produce an output of type ⁠ $\tau$ ⁠.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] By convention, $\to$ associates to the right: $\sigma \to \tau \to \rho$ is read as ⁠ $\sigma \to (\tau \to \rho )$ ⁠.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] To define the types, a set of *base types*, ⁠ B ⁠, must first be defined.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] These are sometimes called *atomic types* or *type constants*.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] A set of *term constants* is also fixed for the base types.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] For example, it might be assumed that one of the base types is nat, and its term constants could be the natural numbers.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] The syntax of the simply typed lambda calculus is essentially that of the lambda calculus itself.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] The term $x{\mathbin {:}}\tau$ denotes that the variable x is of type ⁠ $\tau$ ⁠.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] A variable reference x is *bound* if it is inside of an abstraction binding ⁠ x ⁠.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] A term is *closed* if there are no unbound variables.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] Whereas in typed lambda calculus every *abstraction* (i.e. function) must specify the type of its argument.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] To define the set of well-typed lambda terms of a given type, one defines a typing relation between terms and types.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] First, one introduces *typing contexts*, or *typing environments* $\Gamma ,\Delta ,\dots$ , which are sets of typing assumptions.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] A *typing assumption* has the form ⁠ $x{\mathbin {:}}\sigma$ ⁠, meaning variable x has type ⁠ $\sigma$ ⁠.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] The *typing relation* $\Gamma \vdash e{\mathbin {:}}\sigma$ indicates that e is a term of type $\sigma$ in context ⁠ $\Gamma$ ⁠.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] In this case e is said to be *well-typed* (having type ⁠ $\sigma$ ⁠).
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] Instances of the typing relation are called *typing judgments*.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] The validity of a typing judgment is shown by providing a *typing derivation*, constructed using typing rules (wherein the premises above the line allow us to derive the conclusion below the line).
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] Term constants have the appropriate base types.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] If, in a certain context with x having type ⁠ $\sigma$ ⁠, e has type ⁠ $\tau$ ⁠, then, in the same context without ⁠ x ⁠, ⁠ $\lambda x{\mathbin {:}}\sigma .~e$ ⁠ has type ⁠ $\sigma \to \tau$ ⁠.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] These are the typed lambda calculus representations of the basic combinators of combinatory logic.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] Each type $\tau$ is assigned an order, a number ⁠ $o(\tau )$ ⁠.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] That is, the order of a type measures the depth of the most left-nested arrow.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] Broadly speaking, there are two different ways of assigning meaning to the simply typed lambda calculus, as to typed languages more generally, variously called intrinsic vs. extrinsic, ontological vs. semantical, or Church-style vs.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] An intrinsic semantics only assigns meaning to well-typed terms, or more precisely, assigns meaning directly to typing derivations.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] This has the effect that terms differing only by type annotations can nonetheless be assigned different meanings.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] For example, the identity term $\lambda x{\mathbin {:}}{\mathtt {int}}.~x$ on integers and the identity term $\lambda x{\mathbin {:}}{\mathtt {bool}}.~x$ on Booleans may mean different things.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] (The classic intended interpretations are the identity function on integers and the identity function on Boolean values.) In contrast, an extrinsic semantics assigns meaning to terms regardless of typing, as they would be interpreted in an untyped language.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] In this view, $\lambda x{\mathbin {:}}{\mathtt {int}}.~x$ and $\lambda x{\mathbin {:}}{\mathtt {bool}}.~x$ mean the same thing (i.e., the same thing as ⁠ $\lambda x.~x$ ⁠).
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] The distinction between intrinsic and extrinsic semantics is sometimes associated with the presence or absence of annotations on lambda abstractions, but strictly speaking this usage is imprecise.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] It is possible to define an extrinsic semantics on annotated terms simply by ignoring the types (i.e., through type erasure), as it is possible to give an intrinsic semantics on unannotated terms when the types can be deduced from context (i.e., through type inference).
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] The essential difference between intrinsic and extrinsic approaches is just whether the typing rules are viewed as defining the language, or as a formalism for verifying properties of a more primitive underlying language.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] Most of the different semantic interpretations discussed below can be seen through either an intrinsic or extrinsic perspective.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] The simply typed lambda calculus (STLC) has the same equational theory of βη-equivalence as untyped lambda calculus, but subject to type restrictions.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] holds whenever $\Gamma \vdash t{:}\sigma \to \tau$ and x does not appear free in ⁠ t ⁠.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] The advantage of typed lambda calculus is that STLC allows potentially nonterminating computations to be cut short (that is, *reduced*).
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] Likewise, the operational semantics of simply typed lambda calculus can be fixed as for the untyped lambda calculus, using call by name, call by value, or other evaluation strategies.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] As for any typed language, type safety is a fundamental property of all of these evaluation strategies.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] Additionally, the strong normalization property described below implies that any evaluation strategy will terminate on all simply typed terms.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] The simply typed lambda calculus enriched with product types, pairing and projection operators (with $\beta \eta$ -equivalence) is the internal language of Cartesian closed categories (CCCs), as was first observed by Joachim Lambek.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] Given any CCC, the basic types of the corresponding lambda calculus are the objects, and the terms are the morphisms.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] Conversely, the simply typed lambda calculus with product types and pairing operators over a collection of base types and given terms forms a CCC whose objects are the types, and morphisms are equivalence classes of terms.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] There are typing rules for *pairing*, *projection*, and a *unit term*.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] Given two terms $s{\mathbin {:}}\sigma$ and ⁠ $t{\mathbin {:}}\tau$ ⁠, the term $(s,t)$ has type ⁠ $\sigma \times \tau$ ⁠.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] Likewise, if one has a term ⁠ $u{\mathbin {:}}\tau _{1}\times \tau _{2}$ ⁠, then there are terms $\pi _{1}(u){\mathbin {:}}\tau _{1}$ and $\pi _{2}(u){\mathbin {:}}\tau _{2}$ where the $\pi _{i}$ correspond to the projections of the Cartesian product.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] The *unit term*, of type 1, written as $()$ and vocalized as 'nil', is the final object.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] This last is read as "*if t has type 1, then it reduces to nil*".
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] The above can then be turned into a category by taking the types as the objects.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] The morphisms $\sigma \to \tau$ are equivalence classes of pairs $(x{\mathbin {:}}\sigma ,t{\mathbin {:}}\tau )$ where *x* is a variable (of type ⁠ $\sigma$ ⁠) and *t* is a term (of type ⁠ $\tau$ ⁠), having no free variables in it, except for (optionally) *x*.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] The set of terms in the language is the closure of this set of terms under the operations of abstraction and application.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] This correspondence can be extended to include "language homomorphisms" and functors between the category of Cartesian closed categories, and the category of simply typed lambda theories.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] Part of this correspondence can be extended to closed symmetric monoidal categories by using a linear type system.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] From his logistic method Church 1940 p.58 laid out an axiom schema, p.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] 60, which Henkin 1949 filled in with type domains (e.g. the natural numbers, the real numbers, etc.).
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] 146 described how Church's logistic method could seek to provide a foundation for mathematics (Peano arithmetic and real analysis), via model theory.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] The presentation given above is not the only way of defining the syntax of the simply typed lambda calculus.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] One alternative is to remove type annotations entirely (so that the syntax is identical to the untyped lambda calculus), while ensuring that terms are well-typed via Hindley–Milner type inference.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] The inference algorithm is terminating, sound, and complete: whenever a term is typable, the algorithm computes its type.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] Another alternative presentation of simply typed lambda calculus is based on **bidirectional type checking**, which requires more type annotations than Hindley–Milner inference but is easier to describe.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] The type system is divided into two judgments, representing both *checking* and *synthesis*, written $\Gamma \vdash e\Leftarrow \tau$ and $\Gamma \vdash e\Rightarrow \tau$ respectively.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] Operationally, the three components ⁠ $\Gamma$ ⁠, ⁠ e ⁠, and $\tau$ are all *inputs* to the checking judgment ⁠ $\Gamma \vdash e\Leftarrow \tau$ ⁠, whereas the synthesis judgment $\Gamma \vdash e\Rightarrow \tau$ only takes $\Gamma$ and e as inputs, producing the type $\tau$ as output.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] Observe that rules [1]–[4] are nearly identical to rules (1)–(4) above, except for the careful choice of checking or synthesis judgments.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] The types of term constants are fixed and can be synthesized.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] To check that $\lambda x.~e$ has type $\sigma \to \tau$ in some context, we extend the context with $x{\mathbin {:}}\sigma$ and check that e has type ⁠ $\tau$ ⁠.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] If $e_{1}$ synthesizes type $\sigma \to \tau$ (in some context), and $e_{2}$ checks against type $\sigma$ (in the same context), then $e_{1}~e_{2}$ synthesizes type ⁠ $\tau$ ⁠.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] Observe that the rules for synthesis are read top-to-bottom, whereas the rules for checking are read bottom-to-top.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] Note in particular that we do **not** need any annotation on the lambda abstraction in rule [3], because the type of the bound variable can be deduced from the type at which we check the function.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] If e checks against type ⁠ $\tau$ ⁠, then the explicitly annotated term $(e{\mathbin {:}}\tau )$ synthesizes ⁠ $\tau$ ⁠.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] Because of these last two rules coercing between synthesis and checking, it is easy to see that any well-typed but unannotated term can be checked in the bidirectional system, so long as we insert "enough" type annotations.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] And in fact, annotations are needed only at β-redexes.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] Given the standard semantics, the simply typed lambda calculus is strongly normalizing: every sequence of reductions eventually terminates.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] This is because recursion is not allowed by the typing rules: it is impossible to find types for fixed-point combinators and the looping term ⁠ $\Omega =(\lambda x.~x~x)(\lambda x.~x~x)$ ⁠.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] Recursion can be added to the language by either having a special operator ${\mathtt {fix}}_{\alpha }$ of type $(\alpha \to \alpha )\to \alpha$ or adding general recursive types, though both eliminate strong normalization.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] Unlike the untyped lambda calculus, the simply typed lambda calculus is not Turing complete.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] All programs in the simply typed lambda calculus halt.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/simply-typed-lambda-calculus] For the untyped lambda calculus, there are programs that do not halt, and moreover there is no general decision procedure that can determine whether a program halts.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/subject-reduction] In type theory, a type system has the property of **subject reduction** (also **subject evaluation**, **type preservation** or simply **preservation**) if evaluation of expressions does not cause their type to change.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/subject-reduction] Intuitively, this means one would not like to write an expression, in say Haskell, of type Int, and have it evaluate to a value *v*, only to find out that *v* is a string.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/subject-reduction] Together with progress, it is an important meta-theoretical property for establishing type soundness of a type system.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/subject-reduction] The opposite property, if Γ ⊢ *e*2 : *τ* and *e*1 → *e*2 then Γ ⊢ *e*1 : *τ*, is called **subject expansion**.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/subject-reduction] It often does not hold as evaluation can erase ill-typed sub-terms of an expression, resulting in a well-typed one.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/type-rule] In type theory, a **typing rule** is an inference rule that describes how a type system assigns a type to a syntactic construction.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/type-rule] These rules may be applied by the type system to determine if a program is well-typed and what type expressions have.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/type-rule] A prototypical example of the use of typing rules is in defining type inference in the simply typed lambda calculus, which is the internal language of Cartesian closed categories.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/type-rule] Typing rules specify the structure of a *typing relation* that relates syntactic terms to their types.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/type-rule] Syntactically, the typing relation is usually denoted by a colon, so for example $e:\tau$ denotes that an expression e has type $\tau$ .
[src:simply-typed-lambda/type-rule] The rules themselves are usually specified using the notation of natural deduction.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/type-rule] Each rule states that the conclusion below the line may be derived from the premises above the line.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/type-rule] The first two rules have no premises above the line, so they are axioms.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/type-rule] The third rule has premises above the line (specifically, three premises), so it is an inference rule.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/type-rule] In programming languages, the type of a variable depends on where it is bound, which necessitates context-sensitive typing rules.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/type-rule] These rules are given by a *typing judgment*, usually written $\Gamma \vdash e:\tau$ , which states that an expression e has type $\tau$ under a typing context $\Gamma$ that relates variables to their types.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/type-rule] Not all systems of typing rules directly specify a type checking algorithm.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/type-rule] For example, the typing rule for applying a parametrically polymorphic function in the Hindley–Milner type system requires "guessing" the appropriate type at which the function should be instantiated.
[src:simply-typed-lambda/type-rule] Adapting a declarative rule system to a decidable algorithm requires the production of a separate, algorithmic system that can be proven to specify the same typing relation.
